00:01:35.340 --> 00:01:41.350
is the mountains over here, okay? Here in
Seattle in Western Washington, we have double

00:01:41.350 --> 00:01:45.570
protection against the cold air and the interior
of the continent. Now, you have very cold

00:01:45.570 --> 00:01:50.260
air that hits Eastern Montana and the central
part of the continent, but we have two blocks:

00:01:50.260 --> 00:01:57.320
one is the Rockies and one is the Cascades.
And the way it works is this. It's an East-West

00:01:57.320 --> 00:02:02.660
cross section here, so it's cold here in Montana
and what happens is, the coldest air is basically

00:02:02.660 --> 00:02:07.460
held back by the mountains. Some air that
does get across, it sinks down into Eastern

00:02:07.460 --> 00:02:11.629
Washington. But when air sinks, it warms,
because you're going from relatively below

00:02:11.629 --> 00:02:16.810
pressure here to high pressure down here.
And so when you have air that goes to high

00:02:16.810 --> 00:02:21.140
pressure, it's compressed and it's warm, just
like in a bicycle pipe, you know, a bicycle

00:02:21.140 --> 00:02:25.000
pump warms up as you pump it up. And then
we have another filter. We have relatively

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:30.170
cooler air in Eastern Washington, only the--so
some mild array gets across and as it sinks,

00:02:30.170 --> 00:02:35.260
it warm up further. So because that we have
these two mountain barriers, we cannot get

00:02:35.260 --> 00:02:40.569
the primo cold air from the interior of the
continent getting here into Western Washington,

00:02:40.569 --> 00:02:47.090
unless it's the most unusual of circumstances.
The other thing is the Pacific. You know,

00:02:47.090 --> 00:02:51.599
the Pacific Ocean--and this is the SSTs, the
sea surface temperatures of the Pacific--it

00:02:51.599 --> 00:02:56.400
really is pretty mild and we're talking about
the winter, you know, temperature offshore

00:02:56.400 --> 00:03:01.180
here maybe 50 degrees and it's just not that
much different during the summer time. Weather

00:03:01.180 --> 00:03:04.239
tends to come from the West to move to the
East. We're in the mid-latitudes. The weather

00:03:04.239 --> 00:03:09.450
moves this way. And the air moves generally
that way as well. So, during the winter time,

00:03:09.450 --> 00:03:13.019
you know, we can't get the cold air from the
interior, the air is going over the Pacific,

00:03:13.019 --> 00:03:18.700
which is relatively mild, and so we just can't
get that cold. In the summer time, which we

00:03:18.700 --> 00:03:22.730
only have high pressure out here, we have
some air coming in towards us off the ocean,

00:03:22.730 --> 00:03:26.200
and that keeps the temperatures relatively
low. I'm sure, you know, it's relatively low

00:03:26.200 --> 00:03:32.400
in the summer time. So it's the mountains
and the ocean. The other thing to keep in

00:03:32.400 --> 00:03:37.459
mind is how much mountains affect precipitation.
And, you know, I don't think I'm shocking

00:03:37.459 --> 00:03:41.659
anybody to talk about this. When air rises,
it tends to cool, right, because it's expanding,

00:03:41.659 --> 00:03:46.219
right? You come from high pressure to low
pressure and when air expands, it cools. And

00:03:46.219 --> 00:03:50.180
the amount of moisture air can hold depends
on temperature. Warm air could hold more moisture

00:03:50.180 --> 00:03:55.569
than cold air. And so when it rises, it cools
and eventually, you know, it maybe able to

00:03:55.569 --> 00:03:59.269
hold the moisture down here when it's warm,
but when it's colder, eventually, it gets

00:03:59.269 --> 00:04:02.419
to a stage where you can just barely hold
the moisture to start it off with. You push

00:04:02.419 --> 00:04:07.599
it any further, you get cloud droplets and
precipitation. So rising air, just cooling

00:04:07.599 --> 00:04:13.659
and condensation, cloud precipitation, sinking
is just the opposite. You get warming and

00:04:13.659 --> 00:04:18.000
drying. And so, you know, this is the pattern
we see all over the Northwest: up with rain

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:24.370
and clouds, sinking, the opposite. And it's
just so dramatic, it's amazing. During the

00:04:24.370 --> 00:04:28.470
winter time, the winds set to be out of the
Southwest, okay, coming off the Pacific. So

00:04:28.470 --> 00:04:33.030
air rises on the Olympics over here, and you
get this tremendous rainfall. You get 150,

00:04:33.030 --> 00:04:38.550
sometimes 200 inches on this side of the Olympics.
And as the air sinks down into Sequim in this

00:04:38.550 --> 00:04:46.180
area--you know, this is the famous rain shadow--you
may have 15, 18 inches in the area here. That's

00:04:46.180 --> 00:04:51.720
a tremendous variability. And you have the
same thing to a lesser degree on the Cascades,

00:04:51.720 --> 00:04:56.771
enhancement on one side and much less precipitation
on the other. So, you know, on one side of

00:04:56.771 --> 00:05:02.280
the Olympics, you got a rainforest and then
the other side, you have Sequim. It was actually

00:05:02.280 --> 00:05:08.169
cacti that are natural. And, you know, I get
