&gt;&gt; Can you tell us a little bit more about
probcast, the com site you mentioned?

00:36:51.250 --> 00:36:57.400
&gt;&gt; MASS: Right. Okay. Now, the traditional
technology of weather forecasting is dependent

00:36:57.400 --> 00:37:04.260
upon numerical simulation. And so, [INDISTINCT]
work is we get all the information from the

00:37:04.260 --> 00:37:10.580
entire planet, okay, then we will have to
create a 3-dimensional description of the

00:37:10.580 --> 00:37:15.020
atmosphere, then we run our models, which
are called the primitive equations. These

00:37:15.020 --> 00:37:30.480
are the equations that describe the basic
physics of the atmosphere and we're able to

00:37:30.480 --> 00:37:37.290
then use that to simulate into the future,
okay? So the traditional way of forecasting

00:37:37.290 --> 00:37:44.260
was to do it once. The best shot of what you
think the initial state is, the best model,

00:37:44.260 --> 00:37:53.060
you forecast into the future, okay? We call
that deterministic forecasting. And that's

00:37:53.060 --> 00:37:59.830
where everything is kind of dependent upon
right now. But that is completely dishonest

00:37:59.830 --> 00:38:04.170
in a way, because there's all kind of uncertainties
there, right? Uncertainties in the initial

00:38:04.170 --> 00:38:09.090
state, there's uncertainties in the model.
For Jeff Renard or some TV guy to say, "The

00:38:09.090 --> 00:38:14.720
temperature three days from now is going to
be exactly that temperature is ridiculous."

00:38:14.720 --> 00:38:20.330
There is always uncertainty. The new way of
forecasting, the way that's going to dominate

00:38:20.330 --> 00:38:28.670
the century is probabilistic forecasting.
And the way it works is, you don't do one

00:38:28.670 --> 00:38:38.450
computer simulation. You do 50, you do 100,
you do 200, each slightly different, each

00:38:38.450 --> 00:38:46.040
reasonable differently. So you'll have a multitude
of forecast and you can use those multitudes

00:38:46.040 --> 00:38:53.930
of forecasting to get an idea of probabilities.
A gross example is, if half the simulation

00:38:53.930 --> 00:39:07.150
say it's going to rain and the half of it
says it won't rain, then you have, you know,

00:39:07.150 --> 00:39:13.840
it's 50 percent, okay? Now, probcast takes
it one step farther. We now have a collection

00:39:13.840 --> 00:39:27.800
of these forecasts. We call this the sum of
forecasts. It does statistical post-processing

00:39:27.800 --> 00:39:34.910
to optimize the probabilistic forecast versus,
you know--maybe one of those computer models

00:39:34.910 --> 00:39:42.760
are not as good as the other one recently.
It will weigh that one less. Anyway, it can

00:39:42.760 --> 00:39:45.650
massage statistically to produce a statistical
forecast that's optimal. And that's what the

00:39:45.650 --> 00:39:49.011
probcast--probcast stands for probability
forecast. And so, that's the--this is the

